I'm working on async-streams for C# 8.0. Part of the feature is async-iterator methods, which allow both `yield` statements and `await` expressions to be used. Under the cover, we generate a state machine like for regular async methods, but also make use of `ManualResetValueTaskSourceLogic` and `IValueTaskSource`.

The problem is that all our tests for this feature work on the desktop runtime, but hang on Core runtime.  It looks like all the threads are waiting, with no progress made.
It's worth noting that the generated IL was verified to work outside of the test harness (xunit, AssemblyLoadContext).
@jaredpar, @jeffschwMSFT and I tried debugging to get a clue what is going on, but we were not able to find out what the threads are waiting for.

We need some help to investigate this issue. Thanks
Below are the details for repro'ing.

Repro steps:
1.	Unzip the repro folder from `\\jcouvdev\shared-dumps\async-iterators-coreclr\repro.zip`
2.	Open a command prompt in that folder
3.	Run `repro.cmd` (note this requires a connection to corpnet, as it will access some binaries from my nuget cache, which I was not able to bundle into the repro folder)

Outcome:
```
repro> repro.cmd

xUnit.net Console Runner (64-bit .NET Core 4.6.26614.01)
  Discovering: Microsoft.CodeAnalysis.CSharp.Emit.UnitTests
  Discovered:  Microsoft.CodeAnalysis.CSharp.Emit.UnitTests
  Starting:    Microsoft.CodeAnalysis.CSharp.Emit.UnitTests
… xunit hangs …
```

Expected:
Test should complete and succeed.

Some background:
For this repro, I picked one test (AsyncIteratorWithAwaitCompletedAndOneYieldAndOneInvocation), which compiles and executes the code below.
The repro uses the `2.0.7` runtime.

```C#
using static System.Console;
class C
{
    static async System.Collections.Generic.IAsyncEnumerable<int> M() // this code gets compiled into C.<M>d__0.MoveNext()
    {
        Write(""1 "");
        await System.Threading.Tasks.Task.CompletedTask;
        Write(""2 "");
        yield return 3;
        Write(""4 "");
    }
    static async System.Threading.Tasks.Task Main()
    {
        Write(""0 "");
        foreach await (var i in M())
        {
            Write($""{i} "");
        }
        Write(""Done"");
    }
}
```
The result of this compilation is available in the `binaries` sub-folder, as the binary with the GUID name.

Some Orleans users have hit an issue when running on .NET Core 2.1 with TieredCompilation enabled. After investigation, I believe the issue is a JIT bug related to TieredCompilation.

Repro gist: https://gist.github.com/ReubenBond/b5bdf98423d5279a8e9ae63a5e6e8f0a

In the repro, the line `return buff[offset];` will return `buff[0]` when TieredCompilation is enabled and `buff[1]` (correct) when TieredCompilation is disabled.

```C#
byte[] CheckLength(out int offset)
{
    // In the original code, this logic is more complicated.
    // It's simplified here to demonstrate the bug.
    offset = 1;
    return currentBuffer;
}

public byte ReadByte()
{
    int offset;
    var buff = CheckLength(out offset);
    return buff[offset];
}
```

We have advised the affected users to disable TieredCompilation for now, as a workaround.

